American Water Services, Inc. conducted a process hazard analysis of the chlorine process.  The process hazard analysis team consisted of American Water Services personnel knowledgable in process operation and maintenance and knowledgeable in the process hazard analysis process.  The process hazard analysis team used a "what-if / checklist" technique and recommendations were compiled and are being  implemented.

American Water Services, Inc. had developed standard operating procedures (SOPs) that provide system description, specifications and operating steps for the chlorine system.  The SOPs address the start-up, shutdown, inspections, temporary operation, emergency procedures and trouble-shooting.  SOPs to provide for mechanical integrity of the chlorine process equipment rely on manufacturer's recommended approaches.  The RMP contains details of this approach.

Our prevention measures include the use of:

-chorine detectors and alarms to rapidly alert operators to any problems;
-process safety information to document the safe process design;
-process hazards analyses to evaluaate the chemical and process hazards;
-operating procedures to ensure that the system is operated safely;
-maintenance, inspection and testing to ensure that the system is maintained according to applicable standards and manufacturer's recommendations;
-training, hot work permits (if ever required), contractor safety and employee participation programs to ensure that all employees and contractors working on and around the processes are aware of the hazards, can perform their job duties safely and know the actions to be taken in an emergency;
-management of change and prestartup safety reviews to ensure that changes are documented, analyzed and kept within the design basis;
